revision.text:
{{about|the idiom|other uses|Between the Devil and the Deep Blue Sea (disambiguation)}}
{{refimprove|date=September 2009}}
{{dictdef}}
{{wiktionary}}

'''"Between the devil and the deep blue sea"''' is an [[idiom]] meaning a [[dilemma]]—i.e., to choose between two undesirable situations  (equivalent to "[[wiktionary:between a rock and a hard place|between a rock and a hard place]]").

The first recorded citation of "the Devil and the deep sea" in print is in [[Robert Monro]]'s ''His expedition with the worthy Scots regiment called Mac-keyes'', 1637: "I, with my partie, did lie on our poste, as betwixt the devill and the deep sea."

